# Gold ICT Pro Liquidity Engine — Strategy Framework Architecture Review

## Q1 — Architecture A vs B

**Recommend B**, with one refinement.

| | A (flat) | B (layered) |
|---|---|---|
| Coupling | Router directly owns entry logic | Router only dispatches; strategies own their own logic |
| Testability | Hard to isolate — router and entry logic are one blob | Each strategy is independently testable against a fixed `ValidationSummary` |
| Extensibility | Adding a strategy means touching router internals | Adding a strategy means adding a new module + registry entry |
| Pine Script fit | Tempting because Pine has no interfaces, but leads to monolithic `if/else` sprawl | Still works in Pine via dispatch table pattern (see Q8) |

A collapses "selection" and "execution" into one responsibility, which is exactly the kind of coupling that makes future changes expensive. B keeps the Router as a thin **dispatcher**, and pushes all strategy-specific logic into isolated `Individual Strategy` modules that share a contract.

**Refinement:** insert an **Arbitration** stage between `StrategyResult` and `EntryResult`, since you'll have multiple strategies producing multiple `StrategyResult`s, not one:

```
ValidationSummary
     ↓
Strategy Router  (dispatch)
     ↓
[Strategy A] [Strategy B] [Strategy C]   → each emits StrategyResult
     ↓
Arbitration Layer  (resolve conflicts/duplicates)
     ↓
EntryResult
```

This is really "B" but made explicit that Router output is a **set**, not a single result.

