## Q4 — StrategyResult Contract

Yes — **every strategy must produce an identical output contract.** This is the single most important design decision for scalability (Q7 depends entirely on this). Without a uniform contract, Arbitration and Trade Manager would need per-strategy special-casing, which defeats the entire point of a router.

Improved contract:

```
StrategyResult
├── strategyId          (string, unique, stable across versions)
├── strategyVersion      (string — NEW: lets you evolve a strategy without breaking history/replay)
├── direction            (enum: BUY | SELL | NONE)
├── entryApproved         (bool)
├── confidence           (float 0–1, normalized — NEW: must be comparable across strategies)
├── reason                (string/enum code, human-readable + machine-parsable — split into reasonCode + reasonText)
├── integrityFlag         (enum: OK | DEGRADED | INVALID — NEW: distinguishes "no trade" from "strategy couldn't run properly")
├── timestamp             (must match/derive from ContextSnapshot time, not wall-clock, for determinism)
├── inputsHash            (NEW — optional but valuable: hash of the ValidationSummary it evaluated, for audit/debugging)
```

Key improvements over your draft:
- **`confidence` must be normalized** (0–1) across all strategies, or "highest confidence" comparisons in Q5 are meaningless. Enforce this at the contract level, not by convention.
- **`reason` split into code + text** — arbitration logic should never parse free text.
- **`integrityFlag`** is critical: a strategy that fails to evaluate (bad data, missing input) must not silently look identical to a strategy that legitimately says "no trade." This distinction prevents a nasty silent-failure class of bug.
- **`strategyVersion`** — you will change strategy logic over time; without a version field, you cannot audit which logic version produced a historical result.
- **`timestamp` should derive from the frozen `ContextSnapshot`**, not real-world clock, to keep everything deterministic and replayable (important for backtesting a frozen pipeline).

