## Q6 — Two Strategies Disagree (BUY vs NO TRADE)

Arbitration happens in the same **Arbitration Layer**, using an explicit conflict-resolution policy — not ad hoc logic buried in the Router or Trade Manager.

Recommended default policy: **conservative veto** — if any active, high-integrity strategy returns `entryApproved = false` while another returns `true` for the same direction, the default should lean toward **no trade**, unless you explicitly configure a "majority vote" or "confidence-weighted" policy instead.

Why conservative-by-default: in an ICT/SMC context, disagreement usually means the setup is ambiguous (e.g., structure looks valid but session timing doesn't confirm) — trading through disagreement is a common source of false-positive losses. But this should be a **named, swappable policy** (`ArbitrationPolicy: CONSERVATIVE | MAJORITY | WEIGHTED | HIGHEST_CONFIDENCE`), so you can backtest different arbitration strategies against the same strategy outputs without touching strategy code.

`EntryResult` should also carry an audit trail: which strategies ran, what each returned, and which policy resolved the conflict — this is what will let you debug "why didn't this trade fire" six months from now.

